materials_v1.1_fewshot_314_gen50_sel30_c.summary: The study investigates the link between organophosphate pesticide exposure and ADHD in U.S. children aged 8-15, using data from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey. It found that higher urinary concentrations of dialkyl phosphate metabolites, particularly dimethyl alkylphosphates, were associated with increased odds of ADHD diagnosis. The findings suggest that common levels of organophosphate exposure may contribute to ADHD prevalence, warranting further prospective studies to determine causality.
